<section class="hero">
  <h1>How Much <em>Cash?</em></h1>
  <div class="hero-subtitle">The other end of the sizing question &mdash; for the reader who already went all in.</div>
  <p class="subtitle"><a href="/how-much-bitcoin">How Much Bitcoin?</a> ends at a fraction. This page is about the rest of it: how much fiat belongs beside a stack, what that fiat is actually for, and what holding it costs you in the only unit that matters here. Everything below is counted in coins.</p>
</section>

<main class="content-area">

  {% include 'components/tool-framing.njk' %}

  <!-- ════════ §A THE THREE JOBS ════════ -->
  <div class="section-intro hc-prose">
    <p>You hold bitcoin. You owe dollars. Rent, tuition, a new roof, a hospital bill: none of them can be settled in coins, and none of them wait for a good moment. That mismatch is why this page exists. A stack that is 100% hot is not a portfolio with no cash in it, it is a portfolio that has pre-committed to selling bitcoin at whatever price the market happens to be showing on the day life sends a bill.</p>
    <p>A buffer of fiat beside the stack does three jobs, in descending order of weight. The first is that it is a <strong>shock absorber</strong>: money you can spend without touching a coin, so a surprise expense never becomes a forced sale at a bad price. The second is that whatever the shock absorber does not consume is <strong>dry powder</strong>, and if price happens to visit the floor of the channel while the buffer is still intact, that is a contingent bonus, never the plan. The third is <strong>sleep</strong>: the buffer you hold so that you can hold the stack.</p>
    <p>None of that is free, and the price is the point of this page. Every dollar in the buffer is a coin you sold to get it, and the coins do not come back. <a href="/how-much-bitcoin">How Much Bitcoin?</a> concludes at a <em>fraction</em> of Kelly rather than the whole of it, which means even that page's ideal reader ends up holding something that is not bitcoin. This page names what that something is for, and what it costs. The Kelly math is not re-derived here.</p>
  </div>

