  <!-- ════════ §E DRY POWDER ════════ -->
  <section class="hc-section" id="dry-powder">
    <div class="hc-eyebrow">The bonus, not the plan</div>
    <h2 class="hc-h2">Dry powder</h2>
    <div class="hc-prose">
      <p>There is a version of this page that sells a cash buffer as a war chest for buying the bottom. It would contradict a page we have already published. <a href="/wait-or-deploy-now">Wait, or Deploy Now?</a> finds that from most positions in the channel, waiting for a lower entry was the wrong call, and it declines to manufacture a deliberation when the historical answer is to deploy. That page and this one have to agree out loud.</p>
      <p>So the resolution is the honest ordering rather than a louder claim. The buffer exists for the shock. If the shock never comes, and if price happens to visit the floor while the buffer is still whole, then deploying some of it there has historically bought more coins than deploying the same dollars at trend. That is a contingent bonus and it is downstream of the insurance job, which is why the rule above deploys only what the shock did not need, only at the trough, only once. The moment you deploy it, it stops being a buffer, and the next surprise finds you back where this page started.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="hc-readout-block" id="hcDryReadout">&mdash;</div>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════ §F SLEEP + BORROWING ════════ -->
  <section class="hc-section" id="sleep">
    <div class="hc-eyebrow">The last job</div>
    <h2 class="hc-h2">Sleep, and the other way to never sell</h2>
    <div class="hc-prose">
      <p>The third job does not compute. A buffer is also the thing that lets you sit through a drawdown without doing something you will regret, because the bill that would have forced your hand is already covered. The <a href="/bitcoin-allocation-sizing">allocation page</a> puts it as a question worth asking before any of the math: can you hold it? A position you cannot hold through a bad year is not really your position. Some of what a buffer buys is simply the ability to keep the rest.</p>
      <p>There is another answer to never selling, and it deserves its paragraph. <a href="/borrowing-against-your-stack">Borrowing against your stack</a> gets you dollars without a sale, and on paper it dominates a cash buffer: no coins foregone, no premium, no drag. Its failure mode is the whole subject of this page. A credit line against bitcoin is collateralized by bitcoin, so it tightens exactly when bitcoin falls, and the margin call arrives at the same trough where the forced sale would have hurt most. The two options fail at the same moment, and only one of them is still there when it does.</p>
    </div>
    <p class="hc-sharp">A loan against your stack is a buffer that can be taken away at the exact moment you need it.</p>
    <div class="hc-prose">
      <p>That is not an argument against borrowing, which has its own page and its own honest math. It is the reason the two cannot be treated as substitutes for the same job.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════ VERIFY THE MATH ════════ -->
  <section class="hc-section" id="audit">
    <button class="hc-audit-toggle" id="hcAuditToggle" aria-expanded="false">
      <span class="hc-audit-label">Verify the math</span>
      <span class="hc-audit-hint">the year-by-year ledger behind the chart: price, coins on each path, cash, and every event that moved them.</span>
    </button>
    <div id="hcAuditBody2" hidden>
      <button type="button" class="hc-csv-btn" id="hcCsvBtn">Download CSV</button>
      <div class="hc-tablewrap">
        <table class="hc-table">
          <thead id="hcAuditHead"></thead>
          <tbody id="hcAuditBody"></tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="hc-endnote">Each row reproduces from its neighbour. Coins only ever change at a named event: the buffer being raised, a forced sale, or a deployment. Cash only changes at yield, the shock, or a deployment. The whole verdict is two quantities. What the buffer <strong>cost</strong> you is <em>B / P</em> coins to raise, where <em>B</em> is months times monthly expenses and <em>P</em> is the price at the marker, less whatever the leftover cash grows back into by the end. What it <strong>saved</strong> you is the coins the shock did not force you to sell: the cash it absorbed, divided by the trough price. The buffer pays if and only if the second exceeds the first, and the difference between them is exactly the gap between the two paths above, which is why your stack size never enters the comparison.</p>
      <p class="hc-endnote">Two limits are worth naming, because they are where that arithmetic stops applying. If the buffer only covers part of the shock, it still cost the full raise but only saved what its cash could absorb, so a buffer smaller than the shock can lose while looking like it should win. And a shock larger than the whole stack at trough prices sells every coin and still leaves a bill: past that point the buffer is not an optimization, and its cost is no longer the interesting question.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

